"type":"code","lang":"","value":"**Sectionnest**\n\n*(Interactive activity — available in the OLI platform)*","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"oD6lztSLjf"}],"key":"O6reWFZmLb"},{"type":"admonition","children":[{"type":"admonitionTitle","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"aVXJaeBbeO"}],"key":"iLhiAgzCnL"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"Household size in the United States has a mean of 2.6 people and standard deviation of 1.4 people.\n\n(a) What is the probability that a randomly chosen household has more than 3 people?\n\nA normal approximation should not be used here, because the distribution of household sizes would be considerably skewed to the right. We do not have enough information to solve this problem.\n\n(b) What is the probability that the mean size of a random sample of 10 households is more than 3?\n\nBy anyone's standards, 10 is a small sample size. The Central Limit Theorem does not guarantee sample mean coming from a skewed population to be approximately normal unless the sample size is large.\n\n(c) What is the probability that the mean size of a random sample of 100 households is more than 3?\n\nNote: To review how to determine probabilities for z scores, please refer to the Standard Normal Table section of the Random Variables module.\n\nNow we may invoke the Central Limit Theorem: even though the distribution of household size X is skewed, the distribution of sample mean household size $\\bar{X}$ is approximately normal for a large sample size such as 100. Its mean is the same as the population mean, 2.6, and its standard deviation is the population standard deviation divided by the square root of the sample size: $\\frac{\\sigma}{\\sqrt{n}}=\\frac{1.4}{\\sqrt{100}}=.14.$ The z-score for 3 is $\\frac{3-2.6}{\\frac{1.4}{\\sqrt{100}}}=\\frac{0.4}{0.14}=2.86$ The probability of the mean household size in a sample of 100 being more than 3 is therefore P($\\bar{X}$ > 3) = P(Z > 2.86) = P(Z < -2.86) = .0021.\n\nHouseholds of more than 3 people are, of course, quite common, but it would be extremely unusual for the mean size of a sample of 100 households to be more than 3.","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"fo15KGguj5"}],"key":"UUri7GS20c"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The purpose of the next activity is to give guided practice in finding the sampling distribution of the sample mean (","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"TcXTbf96p3"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\bar{X}","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo>ˉ</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bar{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8201em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8201em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2523em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.1667em;\"><span class=\"mord\">ˉ</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","key":"U6mYWMLW3w"},{"type":"text","value":"), and use it to learn about the likelihood of getting certain values of ","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1},"end":{"line":50,"column":1}},"key":"HZUGt83TA7"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\bar{X}","pos